HAPPY BIRTHDAY - FELIZ CUMPLEA√ëOS TO THE RUTA DE LA AMISTAD - MEXICO 68
Station #10 ‚ÄúSundial‚Äù
Artist: Grzegorz Kowalski (POL) - (1942)
Seven cones of identical dimensions, each one spread out in a different direction and position. The tops of two of them have been cut off, and one has been turned upside down. Constructed from  reinforced concrete and standing five metres high, they are painted in various warm tones, from yellow and orange to red and ochre. Thanks to its position, the central cone is the one that receives the full force of the sun. The conical shapes play off one another, creating a sensation of movement and contradictory forces for spectators passing through the area.

HAPPY BIRTHDAY - FELIZ CUMPLEA√ëOS TO THE RUTA DE LA AMISTAD - MEXICO 68
Station #9 / Untitled
Artist: Todd Williams (USA) - (1939)
This seven-metre-high sculpture, made of reinforced concrete, is composed of three elements connected by different circular and oval parts. Together they make up a space, or roof, that offers shelter and allows passage beneath it. The work was originally constructed on a mound of volcanic rock (which is the natural landscape of the area), inside which was the Olympic Village warm-up arena that is still used today.

I am a HUGE sports and athletics fan so I was absolutely geeking out today at the Olympic Museum. Learning the history of these games and seeing the mementos of my biggest athletic heroes was a truly moving moment for me. The communal spirit of the games, when the world sets aside their differences and converges to witness wonders, is unlike any other that I know. 
In order of appearance:
1. The original Olympic flag

2. Jesse Owens - Berlin 1936 - The Nazi Olympics

3. USA Hockey - Lake Placid 1980 - The Miracle on Ice

4. Usain Bolt - Beijing 2008

5. Michael Phelps - Athens 2004

6. USA Basketball - Barcelona 1992 - The Dream Team

7. Michael Johnson - Atlanta 1996

8. Rafa Nadal - Beijing 2008

9. The Olympic medals

10. The Olympic torches
